0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAncestral Pueblo farmers encountered the deep, well watered, and productive soils of the central Mesa Verde region of Southwest Colorado around A.D. 600, and within two centuries built some of the largest villages known up to that time in the U.S. Southwest. But one hundred years later, those villages were empty, and most people had gone. This cycle repeated itself from the mid-A.D. 1000s until 1280, when Puebloan farmers permanently abandoned the entire northern Southwest. Taking an interdisciplinary approach, this book examines how climate change, population size, interpersonal conflict, resource depression, and changing social organization contribute to explaining these dramatic shifts. Comparing the simulations from agent-based models with the precisely dated archaeological record from this area, this text will interest archaeologists working in the Southwest and in Neolithic societies around the world as well as anyone applying modeling techniques to understanding how human societies shape, and are shaped by the environments we inhabit.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aPueblo IndiansxAgricuturexColoradoxMesa Verde National Park. 0aPueblo IndiansxAntiquitiesxColoradoxMesa Verde National Park. 0aPueblo IndiansxHistoryxColoradoxMesa Verde National Park. 0aPueblo IndianszColoradozMesa Verde National ParkxAgricuture. 0aPueblo IndianszColoradozMesa Verde National ParkxAntiquities. 0aPueblo IndianszColoradozMesa Verde National ParkxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Archaeology.2bisacsh1 aKohler, Timothy A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aVarien, Mark D., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gruyter